1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,980
In this lesson, we're going to talk about faceting in multiple directions.

2
00:00:04,980 --> 00:00:08,190
In this way, faceting can be extended to

3
00:00:08,190 --> 00:00:14,940
multivariate cases by having each facet be a bivariate plot instead.

4
00:00:14,940 --> 00:00:18,570
We're going to start by doing our normal imports,

5
00:00:18,570 --> 00:00:21,975
both of our libraries and visualization packages,

6
00:00:21,975 --> 00:00:25,050
but also our fuel economy dataset.

7
00:00:25,050 --> 00:00:28,815
We will also be creating a feature called transmission type,

8
00:00:28,815 --> 00:00:33,675
where we just focus on automatic versus manual transmissions.

9
00:00:33,675 --> 00:00:36,960
Here we're going to use a facet grid of

10
00:00:36,960 --> 00:00:41,995
our DataFrame where the columns are vehicle class.

11
00:00:41,995 --> 00:00:46,495
Now we use our facet grid mapping function to plot

12
00:00:46,495 --> 00:00:54,400
a bivariate scatter plot looking at combined deficiency versus engine size.

13
00:00:54,400 --> 00:01:02,105
Notice that now we get columns where each column is a different vehicle class.

14
00:01:02,105 --> 00:01:05,935
We're not limited to only fascinating by one variable either.

15
00:01:05,935 --> 00:01:08,650
We can also add a row term.

16
00:01:08,650 --> 00:01:18,035
For example we can add now row equals transmission type with the same mapping function.

17
00:01:18,035 --> 00:01:20,425
We now end up with this,

18
00:01:20,425 --> 00:01:23,785
where each row is for a transmission class.

19
00:01:23,785 --> 00:01:27,080
For example this top row is for automatic,

20
00:01:27,080 --> 00:01:34,885
the bottom is for manual transmissions and each column is for different vehicle class.

21
00:01:34,885 --> 00:01:37,830
This is very difficult to read the titles of.

22
00:01:37,830 --> 00:01:44,915
One thing we can do is we can now set the perimeter margin titles equal to true.

23
00:01:44,915 --> 00:01:50,070
This now moves the row titles to the rows for easier reading.

24
00:01:50,810 --> 00:01:59,610
Now the row titles you can find over here on the right side of the plot, much cleaner.

